[normal]Summary of Key Points [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]The effectiveness of commissioners in reducing crime and delivering an effective police service within their police force area[bold].[bold]Since taking up the new role of Commiss
[normal]ioner on the 22 November 2012, th
[normal]e 
[normal]Commissioner and 
[normal]his Deputy Commissioner have worked closely with the Force, 
[normal]partners, stakeholders 
[normal]and the public to create a 
[normal]more holistic approach to problem solving. The focus has been clear, to forge stronger relationships with 
[normal]communities
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]              
[normal]The Commissioner’s vision is to
[normal] be
[normal] the 
[normal]‘People’s Commissioner’, [bold]making himself available to individuals, victims of crime and communities and listen to their concerns. 
[normal]The Commissioners focus is on making people feel safer, remove criminality from their neighbourhoods and tackle the social cause behind offending to permanently interrupt this vicious cycle.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]              
[normal]The Nottinghamshire 
[normal]Police and Crime Plan
[normal] reflects the views and interests of everyone living and working in 
[normal]Nottingham and 
[normal]Nottinghamshire.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]              
[normal]Crime in Nottinghamshire is currently following a national trend which has seen a slight increase in comparison to last year. The increase (+3.2%) has slowed since the start of the year but remains a concern and 
[normal]the Commissioner and Chief Constable are 
[normal]working hard to address this fluctuation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]              
[normal]One way of addressing the rise is 
[normal]through 
[normal]smarter working with our partners
[normal] (Community Safety Partnerships for the City (CDP)
[normal], 
[normal]the County (Safer Neighbourhood Board
[normal] and 
[normal]Local Criminal Justice Board
[normal])
[normal] as well as commissioning services from crime reduction organisations so that we tackl
[normal]e criminality from every angle. 
[normal]It is recognised that Nottinghamshire Police has had a more difficult financial challenge than many other forces, it needs to save £43.6m over the four years of the spending review (between March 2011 and March 2015). This savings requirement is 19% of the overall budget. T
[normal]he Commissioner recognises that there is to be a review
[normal] of the funding formula, with the 
[normal]suggestion that this will not be introduced until 2016-17 at the earliest. 
[normal]The Commissioner is urging that c
[normal]onsultation on the new formula needs to begin now. 
[normal]              
[normal]4.6
[normal]              
[normal]One of the positive developments highlighted in the recent performance update relates to satisfaction levels among victims of crime. 87
[normal].1
[normal]% of victims of crime are completely, very or fairly satisfied with the service they have received from Nottinghamshire Police which is just 2.
[normal]9
[normal]% away from the Police and Crime Plan target of 90%
[normal].
[normal] The County is 87.8% and the City is 86.2%
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.7[bold]              [bold]The role of commissioners in holding th[bold]eir chief constables to account.[bold]The 
[normal]Police and Crime P
[normal]lan sets out 
[normal]the Commissioner’s 
[normal]governance and accountability arrangements
[normal]; these are further outlined in the Commissioner’s Governance Framework
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.8
[normal]              
[normal]A range of performance indicators relating to the 
[normal]seven
[normal] strategic themes contained within the current Police and Crime Plan are monitored by the Office of 
[normal]the 
[normal]Commissioner 
[normal](OPCC) 
[normal]and where performance is identified as a risk the Commissioner holds the Chief Constable to account to seek assurances that action is being taken to address the performance concerns.
[normal] The Commissioner will do this through bilateral weekly meetings with the Chief Constable and through an extended bimonthly 
[normal]Strategic 
[normal]Resource and Performance 
[normal]M
[normal]eeting with the wider Chief Officer Team
[normal]. These meetings are held at various venues across Nottingham and Nottinghamshire
[normal]. In addition, the Commissioner, his Deputy and various members of his office attend a number of Force and Divisional performance meetings where necessary assurances are sought and obtained.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.9[bold]              [bold]The role of police and crime panels in holding their commissioners [bold]to account.[bold]The Nottinghamshire County Council is the host authority for the Nottinghamshire Police and Crime Panel.
[normal] The Panel scrutinises the actions and decisions of the Police and Crime Commissioner and makes sure information is available for the public, enabling them to hold the Commissioner to account.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.10
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]Commissioner provides the Panel with an update report on the performance, key decisions made and activities. Together with providing an update report on Domestic Violence and six monthly Police and Crime Plan monitoring reports.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.11
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]Commissioner’s 
[normal]Police and Crime 
[normal]Plan was scrutinised and approved by the Police and Crime Panel 
[normal]in 
[normal]March
[normal] 2013
[normal].
[normal] The refreshed Plan will be reported to the Panel meeting 
[normal]the 3
[normal] February
[normal] 2014
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.12[bold]              [bold]The division of functions and staff between commissioners and chief constables following the Stage 2 transfers under the Police Reform and[bold] Social Responsibility Act 2011.[bold]As part of the stage two transfer process, 
[normal]the Commissioner was 
[normal]required to advise the Home Secretary of 
[normal]p
[normal]lans for the 
[normal]S
[normal]tage 
[normal]Two T
[normal]ransfer of staff by 16 September 2013
[normal]. 
[normal]The vision for the Stage Two Second Transfer has been agreed between the Commissioner and the Chief Constable.
[normal] The Commissioner’s recommendation is that there is a ‘
[normal]M[bold]aximum Transfer[bold]’ model for Nottinghamshire, which would mean the transfer of all police staff from Operational Frontline, Operational Support and Business Support
[normal] functions to the employment of the Chief Constable. The Deputy Commissioner and the staff employed to work within the Nottinghamshire OPCC will remain under the employment of the Commissioner. In addition the Force will provide business support to the Commissioner as identified within the Working Relationship Agreement and in line with the Policing Protocol Order 2011.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 4.13
[normal]              
[normal]There will be ongoing work to ensure a robust implementation plan once the Home Secretary has approved the Transfer Scheme.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.14[bold]              [bold]T[bold]he role of commissioners [bold]in budget and precept setting.[bold]Together with producing the Police and Crime Plan, the Commissioner has had to make some key decisions which have included setting the precept and the budget for the totality of policing. The Commissioner has also produced his first Annual Report
[normal] which has been shared with the Police and Crime Panel. This Annual Report covers the whole of the financial year from April 2012 to March 2013, and highlights the key commitments made by the Commissioner and the Deputy Commissioner, together with reflecting the performance improvements achieved by the previous Police Authority. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.15
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]C
[normal]ommissioner has set up the Community Safety Partnership Fund specifically to assist small local groups to reduce crime and antisocial behaviour and protect and support victims of crime at neighbourhood level. 
[normal]The projects complement those led by partners through the Community Safety Partnerships in each local authority area. Confirmation of the funding allocation for next year will be in January 2014. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the meantime 
[normal]there will be 
[normal]a 
[normal]review
[normal] of the 
[normal]application process for the Community Safety Partnership Fund 
[normal]to be 
[normal]ready for any future funding rounds.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.16
[normal]              
[normal]The Community Safety Partnership Fund provides small grants of £25,000 or less to voluntary and community groups for projects which 
[normal]assist in reducing crime and protecting victims, witnesses and vulnerable people.
[normal] There were 
[normal]89 applications received at the end of May, requesting £1.4m.  Following appraisal, 28 projects were approved to a value of £351,50.90.  There is a diverse range of projects working in the following areas:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.17
[normal]              
[normal]Some projects contribute towards more than one of the Police and Crime Plan Priorities.  
[normal]All the projects can be viewed at the Commissioners Web Page 
[normal]he[bold]r[bold]e[bold].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.18
[normal]              
[normal]The small grants fund is currently running at £380k which includes match funding for preventative and target hardening work in the County, with a further amount for supporting crime and antisocial behaviour through:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]D
[normal]evelop a multi agency process of identification of girls affected by gangs, identifying risk and developing pathways to enable appropriate support
[normal].
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
